[normal]The mobility of older people in isolated communities[bold].
[normal]Introduction[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]This note 
[normal]is provided by the Chartered Institution of Highways and Transportation, a professional engineering institution with 
[normal]12,000 
[normal]members
[normal] who work in the highways and transportation sector. CIHT members plan, design, build, operate and maintain transport systems
[normal] and infrastructure, whilst respecting the imperatives of improving safety, ensuring economic competitiveness and minimising environmental impact.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This note is concerned with issues affecting the mobility of older people in isolated communities.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Mobility[bold] in isolated communities[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The National Travel Survey, an annual household survey of 
[normal]some
[normal] 
[normal]15
[normal],000 
[normal]to 18,000 
[normal]people, provides data on the number of journeys per year made using different types of transport by residents of different types of area.  Figure 1 sh
[normal]ows the numbers of journeys for people of all ages.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 1  Jour
[normal]neys per year by different means of transport and different types of area (National Travel Survey
[normal], 2003-05)
[normal]The total number of journeys increases slightly as the size of an urban area reduces, but is 
[normal]similar
[normal] for
[normal] large urban areas (population over 250,000) to
[normal] rural areas
[normal] (settlements with 
[normal]populations of less than 3,000)
[normal].  The number of car driver journeys increa
[normal]ses with reducing urban size
[normal] and is particularly large in rural areas.  Walk journeys are similar in number across all urban areas, but fewer in rural areas.  Bus journeys are most frequent in London and the metropolitan conurbations, and very few in rural
[normal] areas.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Although the data in Figures 1 and 2 are for 2003-05, the situation has not changed greatly since that date.  Data corresponding to Figure 1 for 2011-12 is similar, with a small reduction in total trip numbers, a significant reduction in car use a
[normal]nd increase in bus use in London, and a reduction in walking in the larger urban areas, but not in the smaller urban and rural areas.
[normal]  In 2011-12, the total number of journeys in rural areas was fewer than in urban areas.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 2 shows similar data for 
[normal]people in different age groups.
[normal]  Figure 2a shows data for those aged 25 to 49, Figure 2b for those aged 65 to 69 and Figure 2c for those aged 80 and over.
[normal]  These show, for those aged 25 to 49, the importance of driving a car outside of London, and particul
[normal]arly in rural areas, and the relatively little use of buses outside London and the metropolitan conurbations.  For those aged 65 to 69, driving a car is still important, but fewer journeys are as a car driver; bus use in urban (population 25,000 to 250,000
[normal]) and small urban areas increases relative to that by middle-aged people.  For those aged 80 and over, the total number of journeys has reduced considerably
[normal], and car driving in particular. 
[normal] 
[normal]Journeys as a car driver are still more in rural than urban areas,
[normal] as are journeys as a car passenger.  Bus use has increased, relative to that by those aged 65 to 69.
[normal]Figure 2a   Journeys per year by persons aged 25 to 49
[normal](National Travel Survey, 2003-05)
[normal]Figure 2
[normal]b
[normal]   Journeys per year by persons aged 65 to 69
[normal](National Travel Survey, 2003-05)
