[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The proportion of older people in isolated communities[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The ONS publication ‘Regional Trends’ publishes data on the proportion of people of retirement age 
[normal]in individual local authority areas.  This makes it possible to determine the relationship between population density and the percentage of the population of
[normal] retirement age.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 
[normal]3
[normal] shows this relationship for all local authorities in Great Britain in 
[normal]2008.
[normal]  The percentage ranges from almost 35% in some low density areas to under 10% in the hi
[normal]ghest density areas of
[normal] Inner London.
[normal]  The curve is similar, but le
[normal]ss extreme, for Wales on its own, and the range is even smaller for Scotland on its own.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]These data show that older people are disproportionately located in low density areas, where it is difficult and expensive to provide public transport and other servi
[normal]ces, and where people depend on cars to reach the services and facilities that they require.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 3   Population density and percentage of people of retirement age,
[normal]for local authorities, Great Britain  (Regional Trends)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Driving licence holding by [bold]older people[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The percentage of adults holding car driving licences has been increasing, particularly for older people and most r
[normal]apidly for older women (Figure 4
[normal]a and 
[normal]4
[normal]b).  These data are from the National Travel Survey.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 4
[normal]a  Percentage
[normal] of men from different age groups who hold full car driving licences (National Travel Survey)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 4b  Percentage of women from different age groups who hold full car driving licences (National Travel Survey)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For men aged 40 to 70, licence holding h
[normal]as saturated at about 90% of the population.  For older age groups it is rising, for younger it has fallen and is now rather steady.  For women aged 30 to 60, licence holding has saturated at around 80%.  For those aged 60 
[normal]to 69 it 
[normal]appears to be
[normal] saturat
[normal]ing
[normal] at around 70%  For older women it is still increasing
[normal] rapidly
[normal], though from relatively low levels, while for younger women it has fallen but is now rather steady.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The National Travel Survey can provide data on the proportion of driving licence holders 
[normal]who cease to hold a licence at different ages, by following cohorts from the start of reliable NTS data in 1972.  Both men and women start to reduce licence holding after age 70, probably by failing to renew licences rather than by actively surrendering th
[normal]em.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 5 shows the percentages of men and women of various ages who held a car driving licence ten years earlier but have now relinquished it.  Both men and women start to relinquish licences at around age 70.  By age 80, about 15% of women and 10% of
[normal] men who held a licence at age 70, no longer do so.  By age 90, over 40% of women and 20% of men who held licences at age 80, no longer do so.  Thus by age 90, about 60% of women and 35% of men who had held car driving licences at age 70 no longer do so.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Even before relinquishing a driving licence, most older drivers reduce the amount they drive as they age, and progressively avoid stressful driving (night-time, motorways, peak times and busy town centres).
[normal]  This limits the activities that they are able to
[normal] reach by car.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A significant proportion of older people who live in car-dependent areas will stop driving before they are 90 years old.  Those who do will then be dependent on other means of getting about, which may be family and friends, taxis, community
[normal] transport or possibly local bus services.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 5    The percentages of men and women of various ages who held a
[normal]car driving licence ten years earlier but have now relinquished it
[normal](derived from National Travel Survey)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Implications[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Buses are little used in rural areas and small urban areas (populations 25,000 to 3,000).  Most journeys are made by car, either as driver or passenger, or on foot.  In 2011-12, 87% of all journeys 
[normal]in rural areas 
[normal]were made by car or on foot.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The increasin
[normal]g number of older drivers living in low density areas where they have to depend on their car to reach the services and facilities they need for daily life pose
[normal]s
[normal] a large potential problem.  Many will have to stop driving 
[normal]in their 70s or 80s 
[normal]and will then be
[normal] dependent on others for the mobility they need.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]One action that would cost little is a campaign to persuade older people to move from isolated communities to places where they would not be car dependent, before increasing age forces them to restrict or s
[normal]top driving.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A second action would be to support the many excellent local authority programmes to advise older drivers on their ability to continue 
[normal]to 
[normal]driv
[normal]e safely
[normal], many 
[normal]of which provide some training i
[normal]n ways to extend safe driving further into old age.
[normal]&#xa0;
